abstract: APPRENTICES NOT PROPERTY.-The Court-of Queen's Bench has lately decided that where a master has covenanted to instruct his apprentice in any trade, and by selling out his business, incapacitates himself from imparting the promised instruction, he, by that act of itself, violates his covenant, and that he could not justify himself by the fact that he had made arrangements by which his apprentice might be instructed by the party to whom the business was transferred.

abstract: As to the health of the City, all but those in authority have occasion to take comfort and be of good cheer. abstract: This morning (Thursday) about 3 o'clock, a destructive fire broke out in the rear of Stanley-street, about half-way between Church and Victoria-streets, which has proved very destructive. Extending not only in both directions along Stanley-street, but back to Adelaide-street, a great many small houses have been burned, leaving between fifty and one hundred families houseless. The fire broke out about 2 1/2 o'clock,

abstract: ELEVEN MEN CARRIED OVER A CATARACT.-- We imagine that our readers have heard of the narrow escape of eleven raftsmen, a few days ago, who passed over the Chats rapids in a fog, with several cribs of timber. It appears that they were directing the cribs to wards the head of the Victoria slide, but owing to the dense fog passed into the old timber channel, and so over the falls.

abstract: I was an eye witness to the affray which occurred in Chambers-street on Friday evening last, by which JAMES CLORESY came to his death by a fall, occasioned by a blow given by JOHN McINTIRE. I was also present during the examination before the Coroner; and it appears passing strange that in view of the facts and evidence, the jury could have rendered such a verdict as they did.

abstract: During the week, in addition to the cases of cholera which we have reported, several others have occurred. An Irishman named MICHAEL DREW, 34 years old, was reported to have died of cholera Thursday afternoon, at No. 136 Sea-street. EDWARD GROVER, 22 years of age, died at Deer Island, Thursday, of the same disease. MICHAEL MURRAY also died of cholera at No. 110 Sea-street.

abstract: RECORDER'S COURT.--In the temporary absence of Recorder CUTTER, Justice GARDINER presides in the Recorder's Court. On Saturday, Mrs. WILEY, arrested by officer TANNER for drunkenness and attempting the destruction of her own life, was arraigned. Her husband was also arraigned for interfering with the officer at the time of her arrest. Mr. WILEY was fined $3, and his wife was discharged.

abstract: The large Cotton and Woolen Mill, on Jefferson and Miffin-streets, Kensington, was totally destroyed by fire this afternoon, caused it is said by the friction of the machinery. About 300 persons were employed in the building,--mainly females,--and the means of escape by the stairways being cut off by the females, many had to be lowered by ropes, several were hurt by falling. Reports are afloat that several persons perished in the flames.

abstract: On Saturday evening, ALEXANDER HEWITT, a resident of Blackstone, had a serious quarrel with his wife,--both of them being somewhat addicted to the use of intoxicating liquors--and finally the wife fled for refuge to the house of a neighbor named ORIN BROWN. She was followed by her infuriated husband, who upon being refused admittance at the door, proceeded to a window, where seing Mr. BROWN within, he drew a revolving pistol and shot him dead.

abstract: HORRIBLE DEATH OF THREE MEN.--This morning, about 11 o'clock, a terrible accident occurred at the corner of Walnut and Preston-streets, by which three men were almost instantly killed. A privy pit was being dug by the side of an old pit, and preparations were being made to let the contents of the old one into the new one, when suddenly the earth caved in, pouring the entire contents of the privy into the new pit.

abstract: SLAVES AT SOUTHAMTON.--There are now at Southampton, England, eighteen self-emancipated negroes, with five children belonging to them, from the Island of Cuba. The adults were kidnapped from Lagos, and are now about to return there. They were not all kidnapped at one time, but became acquainted with each other in slavery, and associated together from belonging to the same part of Africa.

abstract: Fort Leavenworth (though there is no fort here at all) is on land over five hundred feet above the river.
